In this article, the author reflects on the historical significance of Lafayette Park in Washington, D.C. They mention the Silent Sentinels, a group of women who protested for women's suffrage in front of the White House. The author emphasizes the importance of preserving the history and stories associated with this park. They also mention First Lady Jackie Kennedy's intervention to prevent the demolition of historic buildings around the park. The author expresses gratitude towards the White House Historical Association and its efforts to keep the history alive. They conclude by acknowledging the role of historians in preserving the legacy of Lafayette Park and the People's House.